\begin_layout Standard
Rather than viewing inflation as a monetary phenomenon it is more useful to view it as a conflict over the allocation of resources.
 In this view there will be a number of competing factors which determine the levels of inflationary pressure in the economy.
 On the one hand increasing productivity and labour force participation will tend to decrease inflationary pressures (by making more resources available for distribution),
 while a deterioration (improvement) in the terms of trade will increase (decrease) inflationary pressures.
 Similarly,
 devaluation (revaluation) of the real exchange rate will increase (decrease) inflationary pressures.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equally,
 excess aggregate demand allows agents in some sectors to increase their command over resources,
 by raising relevant prices (including wages).
 However,
 whether they will do so and whether this will result in sustained inflation will depend of a set of factors to be discussed below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The question then is:
 if agents are not (and cannot be) mechanically optimising resources,
 how are prices and inflation determined.
 To say that agents are not rational optimisers,
 setting marginal productivity and marginal desire for leisure equal to prices and wages,
 does not mean that price setting for many goods and services will not respond to the forces of 
